==Perpetrator==
[[Image:Kazmierczak Steven 300.jpg|right|thumb|125px|Steven Phillip Kazmierczak]]
The perpetrator in the shootings was Steven Phillip Kazmierczak, 27 ([[August]] [[1980]] - [[February 14]], [[2008]]), who was born in [[Elk Grove Village]], [[Illinois]], [[United States of America|U.S.A.]]<ref name="suntimes">Pallasch, Abdon K.; Fusco, Chris; Main, Frank; McKinney, Dave; Esposito, Stefano. "[http://www.suntimes.com/news/metro/798150,021708niu.article Portrait of a killer]." ''[[Chicago Sun Times]].'' [[February 16]], [[2008]]. Retrieved on [[February 16]], [[2008]].</ref><ref name="NizzaM">Nizza, Mike; Saulny, Susan; Davey, Monica; Johnson, Dirk; Einhorn, Catrin; Bowley, Graham; Holusha, John. "[http://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/15/us/15cnd-shoot.html Suspect in Campus Attack Is Identified]." ''[[New York Times]].'' [[February 15]], [[2008]]. Retrieved on [[February 15]], [[2008]].</ref> He graduated from [[Elk Grove High School]] in 1998 and went on to study [[sociology]] at [[Northern Illinois University]] (NIU). Though his family moved to [[Florida]] in 2004, Kazmierczak continued his education in Illinois.<ref name="chicagotribune2-14"/><ref name="LATIMES">Heinzmann, David; St. Clair, Stacy. "[http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/nation/la-na-niushooter16feb16,0,3634751.story Illinois gunman was honored student]." ''[[Los Angeles Times]].'' [[February 15]], [[2008]]. Retrieved on [[February 15]], [[2008]].</ref> He enlisted in the [[United States Army]] in September 2001, and was discharged before completing [[basic training]] in February 2002 for unknown reasons.<ref name="ABC_Friedman">Friedman, Emily. "[http://abcnews.go.com/US/story?id=4296984 Who Was the Illinois School Shooter?]." ''[[ABC News]].'' [[February 15]], [[2008]]. Retrieved on [[February 15]], [[2008]].</ref> His mother, Gail, died in Lakeland, Florida in September 2006 from [[amyotrophic lateral sclerosis]] (also known as [[Lou Gehrig]]<U+2019>s disease).<REF NAME="SSDI">[http://search.ancestry.com/cgi-bin/sse.dll?db=ssdi&so=2&rank=0&=%2c%2c%2c%2c%2c%2c%2c%2c1%2c+%2c%2c%2c1%2c+%2c%2c%2c1%2c+%2c%2c%2c1%2c+%2c%2c%2c%2c%2c1%2c+%2c%2c&gsfn=&gsln=kazmierczak&sx=&gs1co=2%2cUSA&gs1pl=12%2cFlorida&year=1998&yearend=2008&sbo=0&sbor=&ufr=0&wp=4%3b_80000002%3b_80000003&srchb=r&prox=1&db=&ti=0&ti.si=0&gss=angs-b Social Security Death Index] maintained by Ancestry.Com.  Retrieved February 15, 2008.</REF><REF NAME="ST-0215">[http://www.suntimes.com/news/metro/796172,CST-NWS-gunman15.article Gunman previously honored by school], February 15, 2008, ''Chicago Sun-Times''.  Retrieved February 15, 2008.</ref><ref name="nbc5">Staff Writer. "[http://www.nbc5.com/news/15316492/detail.html?rss=chi&psp=news A Killer Who Fit In: Kazmierczak Profiled]." ''[http://www.nbc5.com/ nbc5.com/].'' [[February 15]], [[2008]]. Retrieved on [[February 19]], [[2008]].</ref> At the time of Steven's death, his father, Robert, was living in a retirement community in Lakeland.<REF NAME="ST-0215"/>

Kazmierczak graduated from NIU in 2006<ref name="chicagotribune2-14">{{cite news|title=NIU noted gunman's scholarship| url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/chi-shooterfeb15,0,2581284.story|publisher=''[[Chicago Tribune]]''|author=David Heinzmann and Stacy St. Clair|date=[[2008-02-14]] |accessdate=2008-02-15}}</ref> where he received the [[dean's list|Dean's award]] in 2006 and was considered a stand-out, well-regarded student.<ref name="chicagotribune2-14" /> Campus police describe him as a "fairly normal" and "unstressed person."<ref name="ABCSHooter">{{cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/story?id=4296984 |title=Who Was the Illinois School Shooter? |author=Friedman, Emily |publisher=[[ABC News]] |date=[[2008-02-15]] |accessdate=2008-02-15}}</ref>  Faculty, students, and staff "revered" him and there was no indication of any trouble.<ref name="BohnK">Bohn, Kevin. "[http://edition.cnn.com/2008/US/02/15/university.shooting/index.html  Company: Gunman, Virginia Tech shooter used same Web dealer]." ''[[CNN]].'' [[February 15]], [[2008]]. Retrieved on [[February 15]], [[2008]].</ref> NIU President John G. Peters said that he had "a very good academic record, no record of trouble."<ref name="LATIMES"/> Kazmierczak was Vice-President of the NIU chapter of the [[American Correctional Association]]; he had also written about the U.S. correctional system, specifically prisons.<ref>David Heinzmann, David; Smith, Gerry; Zorn, Eric. "[http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/chi-niu-shooter-080216-story,0,59994.story NIU gunman's baffling trail reveals no motive]." ''[[Chicago Tribune]].'' [[February 16]], [[2008]]. Retrieved on [[February 20]], [[2008]].</ref>

In 2006, Kazmierczak, along with two other graduate students and under the lead authorship of a [[sociology]] professor, co-authored an [[academic paper]] entitled, "Self-injury in Correctional Settings: 'Pathology' of Prisons or of Prisoners?"; it was published in the [[academic journal]] ''Criminology & Public Policy''.<ref name ="ThomasJ">Thomas, Jim; Leaf, Margaret; Kazmierczak, Steve; Stone, Josh. "[http://www.blackwell-synergy.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1745-9133.2006.00111.x Self-Injury In Correctional Settings: 'Pathology' of Prisons or of Prisoners?]." ''Criminology & Public Policy'', February 2006, Vol. 5, Iss. 1, 192-202. Retrieved on [[February 15]], [[2008]]. ({{Doi|10.1111/j.1745-9133.2006.00111.x}})</ref>

He was enrolled at NIU in the spring of 2007,<ref name="chicagotribune2-14"/> where he took two courses in [[Arabic]] and a course called "''"Politics of the Middle East"''. His research paper was on the subject of [[Hamas]] and its social service projects.<ref name="Abdelnabi">Abdelnabi, Rasmieyh. 
"[http://www.suntimes.com/news/metro/801984,niugrad021908.article NIU grad recalls shooter as inquisitive, smart, nice]." ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]].'' [[February 20]], [[2008]]. Retrieved on [[March 13]], [[2008]].</ref> He left to begin graduate work in the School of [[Social Work]] at the [[University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign]] (UIUC), where he intended to study [[mental health]] issues. He was enrolled part-time at UIUC during the fall of 2007 and worked from September 24 through October 9 at the [[Rockville Correctional Facility for Women]] near the [[Illinois]]-[[Indiana]] border. His reasons for leaving were unclear; he simply, "did not come back to work," according to Doug Garrison of the Indiana Department of Correction. By early 2008, he was again enrolled full time at UIUC.<ref name="ABC_Friedman"/>

He died of a self-inflicted gunshot wound during this shooting event.<ref name="CNN_0215">{{cite news|title= Source IDs alleged campus gunman who killed 7. |url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/US/02/15/university.shooting/index.html|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=2008-02-15 |accessdate=2008-02-15}}</ref><ref name="ABC_0215">{{cite news|title= Gunman Planned Campus Shooting For At Least Six Days|url=http://www.abcnews.go.com/GMA/story?id=4293081&page=1|publisher=[[ABC]]|date=2008-02-15 |accessdate=2008-02-15}}</ref> [[ABC News]] reports that his behavior seemed to become more erratic in the weeks leading up to the shooting, and that it is believed he stopped taking medication beforehand.<ref name="ABC_Friedman"/> His girlfriend, Jessica Baty, confirmed that Kazmierczak was taking [[Xanax]] ([[Anxiolytic|anti-anxiety]]), [[Ambien]] ([[sedative|sleep aid]]), and [[Prozac]] ([[antidepressant]]), all of which were prescribed to him by a [[psychiatrist]]. She said that he stopped taking Prozac about three weeks prior to the February 14 shooting. She also said that, during their two-year courtship, she had never seen him display violent tendencies and she expressed bewilderment over the cause of the rampage. "He was anything but a monster," Baty said. "He was probably the nicest, most caring person ever."<ref name="BoudreauA">Boudreau, Abbie; Zamost, Scott. "[http://www.cnn.com/2008/CRIME/02/20/shooter.girlfriend/index.html  Girlfriend: Shooter was taking cocktail of 3 drugs]." ''[[CNN]].'' [[February 20]], [[2008]]. Retrieved on [[February 20]], [[2008]].</ref> Since the shooting, authorities have intercepted a number of packages he sent to her, which included such items as a gun holster and bullets, a textbook on [[serial killers]] for her class, the book ''[[The Antichrist (book)|The Antichrist]]'' by [[Friedrich Nietzsche]], and a final note written for her, signed with his first and last name.<ref name="CNN0218">{{cite news|title=  University shooter's girlfriend: 'I couldn't believe it'|url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/US/02/17/shooter.girlfriend/index.html|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=2008-02-18 |accessdate=2008-02-18}}</ref>  The shooting was baffling to those who knew him, as he appeared outgoing and never appeared to have social problems. This has also confused investigators, who have not found a [[suicide note]].<ref name="suntimess">Pallasch, Abdon K.; Korecki, Natasha; Herrmann, Andrew. "[http://www.suntimes.com/news/24-7/797909,CST-NWS-niu16.article Gunman 'somewhat erratic']." ''[[Chicago Sun Times]].'' [[February 16]], [[2008]]. Retrieved on [[February 16]], [[2008]].</ref> Some of Kazmierczak's former NIU roommates described him as a quiet man who usually stayed to himself.  They stated that, while fairly normal, they  did not see him spend much time with other students.  <ref name="CramerKP">Cramer, Kevin P.; Foster, Regan. "[http://www.nwherald.com/articles/2008/02/16/niu_shootings/doc47b5d88b455b5780307923.txt Killer was <U+2018>a quiet, smarter kid<U+2019>]." ''[[Northwest Herald]].'' [[February 16]], [[2008]]. Retrieved on [[February 21]], [[2008]].</ref>

==Reaction==
[[Image:NIU crosses flowers.JPG|right|thumb|Multiple makeshift memorials, including this one near the MLK Commons facing Cole Hall, were established across the NIU campus in the days after the shooting.]]
<!--  Commented out because image was deleted: [[Image:NIU huskies ribbon.jpg|thumb|right|150px|Black ribbon indicating support for the students of NIU|{{puic|1=Image:NIU huskies ribbon.jpg|log=2008 February 15}}]] -->
The university's official website reported the possibility of a gunman on campus at 3:20,<ref name="campus_alert">"[http://www.niu.edu/tragedy/updates.shtml Campus Alert Updates]." ''[[Northern Illinois University]].'' Retrieved on [[February 20]], [[2008]].</ref> within 20 minutes of the shooting.<ref name="AP0215CKJohnson">{{cite news|author=Johnson, Carla K. |title= NIU Shooting Tests New Security Plan|url=http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5j8f-zVFuqoZJSi6Xu6ZPssAnIHdAD8UQI7T01|publisher=[[Associated Press|AP]]|date=2008-02-15 |accessdate=2008-02-19}}<!--If the AP link dies, try "http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory?id=4294957".--></ref> The website then warned students, "There has been a report of a possible gunman on campus. Get to a safe area and take precautions until given the all clear. Avoid the King Commons and all buildings in that vicinity." By 3:40 p.m., all NIU classes were canceled for the remainder of the day and the campus was closed by NIU officials as part of a new security plan devised after the [[Virginia Tech shooting]] 10 months earlier.<ref name="AP0215CKJohnson"/> Students were asked to contact their parents as soon as possible.<ref name="campus_alert"/> All [[Northern Illinois Huskies|NIU Huskie]] sporting events, home and away, through Sunday were canceled.<ref name="ESPN.com">{{cite news|title=NIU sporting events cancelled in wake of shooting|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncaa/news/story?id=3246876|publisher=[[ESPN.com]]|date=[[2008-02-15]] |accessdate=2008-02-15}}</ref> Most students left campus for the weekend.<ref name="GrossB">Gross, Ben. "[http://www.northernstar.info/article/2361/ Campus empties for weekend]." ''Northern Star Online.'' [[February 15]] [[2008]]. Retrieved on [[February 17]] [[2008]].</ref> A spokesman for the [[Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives|ATF]] stated that agents were dispatched to the scene to assist and to help trace the weapons used. The [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] also sent agents to assist. <ref name="CNN_0214"/> According to police, Steven Kazmierczak removed the hard drive from his laptop computer and a computer chip from his cell phone and did not leave a note that could help explain why he chose a geology class on Valentine's Day to open fire. Investigators are expected to spend at least three more weeks until they release a report on the incident.<ref name="Police investigation">"[http://www.foxnews.com/printer_friendly_story/0,3566,331450,00.html Police: Northern Illinois University Gunman Destroyed Evidence to Mislead Investigators]." Retrieved on [[February 26]], [[2008]].</ref>

=== Vigils and memorial services ===
[[Image:Peters NIU shooting.JPG|right|thumb|University President [[John G. Peters|John Peters]] speaks at a campus memorial service held on [[February 24]], [[2008]] at the [[Convocation Center (Northern Illinois University)|Convocation Center]] in memory of the victims of the shooting.]]
Approximately 2,000 gathered on campus on the evening of Friday, February 15, for a [[candlelight vigil]] to commemorate the victims; among other public figures, [[Jesse Jackson]] and [[Robert W. Pritchard]] spoke. Since the day of the shooting, the Lutheran Campus Ministry has held nightly candlelight vigils, and will continue to do so indefinitely.<ref name="NIU Vigils and Services"> "[http://www.niu.edu/tragedy/vigils.shtml Vigils and Services]". ''[[Northern Illinois University]]''. Retrieved on [[February 22]] [[2008]].</ref> All classes and athletic events were canceled through [[February 24]] [[2008]]. Faculty and staff returned to work on Tuesday, February 19, and for the remainder of that week received special information and training to help students upon their return to classes the following week. On February 21, exactly a week after the shooting happened, five minutes of silence were observed from 3:06-3:11 pm CST, accompanied by the tolling of bells throughout the community, at a special ceremony attended by thousands in memory of the victims which was held at the MLK Commons. Moments of silence were also held elsewhere throughout the DeKalb community.<ref name="Daily Chronicle">Daily Chronicle. "[http://www.daily-chronicle.com/articles/2008/02/22/news/news02.txt Listening Together: NIU and the community share moments of silence]." ''Daily Chronicle Online.'' [[February 22]] [[2008]]. Retrieved on [[February 22]] [[2008]].</ref> There was a special memorial service held in the [[Convocation Center (Northern Illinois University)|NIU Convocation Center]] on February 24, the day before classes resumed, in honor of the victims that initiated a set of activities and services aimed at community recovery that will continue throughout the semester. Due to the loss of one week of instructional time in the middle of the semester, an extra week will be added in May.<ref name="PetersJ_NSO">Peters, John. "[http://www.northernstar.info/article/2363/ A message from NIU President John Peters]." ''Northern Star Online.'' [[February 16]] [[2008]]. Retrieved on [[February 17]] [[2008]].</ref>

=== Condolences and tributes ===
[[Image:Bush NIU shooting.jpg|right|thumb|[[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[George W. Bush]] speaks with University president [[John G. Peters|John Peters]] via telephone from the [[White House]] to offer his condolences.]]
[[President of the United States|United States President]] [[George W. Bush]], [[Governor of Illinois|Illinois Governor]] [[Rod Blagojevich]], [[United States Senate|U.S. Senators]] [[Barack Obama]] and [[Richard Durbin|Dick Durbin]], and [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Congressman]] [[Donald A. Manzullo|Donald Manzullo]] offered their personal condolences to NIU President John Peters and the University community in wake of the tragedy, as did many local communities and school districts, and a plethora of universities across the United States.<ref name="FOXNews.com">{{cite news|title=Authorities Identify Former Student Who Killed 5 in Attack at Northern Illinois University|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,330792,00.html|publisher=[[FOX News]]|date=[[2008-02-15]] |accessdate=2008-02-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Condolences: Messages from Other Universities|url=http://www.niu.edu/tragedy/condolences.shtml|accessdate=2008-02-15}}</ref> The [[Chicago Blackhawks]] [[National Hockey League|NHL]] franchise wore NIU Huskies decals on the helmets during their game on Sunday, [[February 17]] [[2008]], versus the [[Colorado Avalanche]]. A moment of silence was also observed before the national anthem at the game, and the team wore the same decal during its next two games at the [[St. Louis Blues (hockey)|St. Louis Blues]] and at home against the [[Minnesota Wild]].<ref name="NHL_blackhawks">{{cite web|author=Staff Writer|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2008/hockey/nhl/02/16/blackhawks.armband/index.html|title=NIU shooting victims to be honored|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=[[February 16]] [[2008]]|accessdate=2008-02-17}}</ref> During [[spring training]], [[Chicago White Sox]] manager [[Ozzie Guillen]] and general manager [[Kenny Williams (baseball)|Ken Williams]] sported NIU caps in tribute to the victims.<ref name="The Courier News">{{cite news|title=Guillen, Williams pay tribute to NIU victims|url=http://www.suburbanchicagonews.com/couriernews/sports/798671,3_2_EL17_B4SOXNOTES_S1.article|publisher=[[Sun-Times Media Group]]|date=[[2008-02-17]] |accessdate=2008-02-19}}</ref> [[Virginia Tech]] had a tribute with students wearing shirts saying "Hokies for Huskies". Students wore these shirts during their basketball game against Georgia Tech on [[February 23]], [[2008]].<ref name="Hokies United"> {{cite news|title=Hokies United: Hokies For Huskies| url=http://www.hokiesunited.org.vt.edu/|publisher=[[Virginia Tech]] |date=[[2008-02-20]] |accessdate=2008-02-20}}</ref> For the 2008 season, the [[Chicago Cubs]] will fly a NIU flag over the grandstands in the out field.<ref name="Chicago Cubs to remember NIU throughout season"> {{cite news|title=Chicago Cubs to remember NIU throughout season| url=/|publisher=[[The Northern Star]] |date=[[2008-03-27]] |accessdate=2008-04-18}}</ref>

===Future of Cole Hall===
On February 26, Illinois Governor [[Rod Blagojevich]] and University President [[John G. Peters]] proposed the demolition of the current Cole Hall. The proposal comes as a response to the "bad" memories of the students who have to attend classes in the building. The proposal would tear down Cole Hall, leave the Cole Hall site as a memorial site, and erect a new building called "Memorial Hall" nearby, at a cost of approximately $40 million.<ref name="Northern Star"> {{cite news|title=Blagojevich, Peters propose $40M to replace Cole| url=http://www.northernstar.info/article.php?id=2466 |publisher=Northern Star |date=[[2008-02-28]] |accessdate=2008-03-15}}</ref>

However, due to mixed emotions on the decision, President Peters sent out a message to all NIU students via their student email accounts, soliciting comments from students and the extended NIU family. In addition, a committee has been established to help reach a consensus on the future of Cole Hall.<ref name="Northern Star Online"> {{cite news|title=Peters announces three-phase process for Cole Hall decision| url=http://www.northernstar.info/article/2605/|publisher=Northern Star |date=[[2008-03-06]] |accessdate=2008-03-15}}</ref>

==Earlier incident and possible threats==
The campus was shut down on [[December 10]] [[2007]], the first day during exam week, after [[graffiti]] was found on a restroom wall warning of a possible shooting. A university spokesman said that the warning, which was discovered December 10, made reference to the [[Virginia Tech massacre]], in which 32 people were killed, but it could not be immediately determined whether the threat was related to the shootings on [[February 14]] [[2008]]. The ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' reported at that time that an unknown person posted the graffiti in the Grant Towers D residence hall, which included a racial slur and the notation "What time? The VA tech shooters{{sic}} messed up w/ having only one shooter."<ref name="msnbc"/> However, NIU President John Peters stated that he did not believe that the December incident is connected to the February 14 shootings.<ref name="FoxNews_Peters-statement">Underwood, Melissa. "[http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,330743,00.html Shooting Reminds Students of Earlier Threat on Campus]." ''[[Fox News]].'' [[February 15]] [[2008]]. Retrieved on [[February 15]] [[2008]].</ref>

A few days before February 14, the university also received another threat of unspecified nature, which was dismissed due to lack of credibility.<ref name="time_mag">{{cite news|url=Gray, Steven|url=http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1714069,00.html|title=How the NIU Massacre Happened|publisher=''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''|date=[[February 16]] [[2008]]|accessdate=2008-02-18}}</ref>

